Q:

Getting the name of a specific instance of a class

I have been having a rather hard time getting the following to work, so I thought I would ask if anyone had any thoughts about the best way to fix it.
Basically, I am trying to instantiate an object of type Bar1, then get either that Bar1 object or a newly instantiated object of Bar1 for a specific named ID (BarX).
When I try to do this, my code won't compile because it takes 2 type arguments for <Bar> (my class) and then requires 1 type argument for <Id>.
Below is a snippet of what I've tried to accomplish (which causes the above error):
private static void Update()
    {
        Bar1 bar = new Bar1(); //I want a specific BarX class

        //if I add a static block here, it compiles fine, but I don't want to have to code the same thing
        //multiple times throughout my application - I thought this might be possible.

        if(BARX.Equals("A1"))
        bar = new Bar1();
        //BARX is a public enum with A1, A2, A3

    }

Is there a way I could accomplish this without having to copy and paste this piece of code into all of my class's Update method declarations? I understand there are good arguments for using the Singleton pattern for this, but is that the best way to go about this?

A:

Use generics and pass the ID to your constructor:
private static void Update()
{
    Bar1 bar = new Bar1<string>("A1"); // I want a specific BarX class
    if (BARX.Equals("A1"))
    bar = new Bar1<string>("A1");
}

By the way: your "public enum" is no enum. It is a string.

