Q:

How to return a promise that will always return a string?

I have a component whose methods return objects such as:
getSomething(): Promise<number> {
  return new Promise((resolve, reject) => {
    // stuff 
    resolve("number");
  });
}

And this component then implements another method which calls this getSomething() method and returns it:
getSomething2(): Promise<string> {
  const something = this.getSomething();
  return something.then((resolve) => resolve("string"))
}

My question is how can I clean this, by getting another method as the Promise returned by getSomething() is a Promise<number>.
In a general way I'm looking for something which will clean this:
getSomething(): Promise<anything> {
  return new Promise((resolve) => {
    // stuff 
    resolve("string");
  });
}

And this component then implements another method such as:
getSomething2(): Promise<string> {
  const something = this.getSomething();
  return something.then((resolve) => resolve("string"))
}

A:

You can implement a factory that will return a Promise<any> that will always resolve to something.  Something like:
const promise = Promise.always(s => s);

You can then use this promise like:
getSomething(): Promise<any> {
  return promise;
}

Then you can pass this promise into getSomething2 like:
getSomething2(): Promise<string> {
  const something = this.getSomething();
  return something.then((resolve) => resolve("string"))
}

