Q:

Does.Net make any changes to the underlying disk while the FileStream keeps reading/writing data

If the file is on an internal SSD, will the file in memory get deleted?
I did something like this:
public ActionResult Download(int id)
{       
    using (FileStream stream = File.Open(Server.MapPath("~/Images/" +
                                                                                       id + ".jpg")))
    {
        byte[] content = GetContentToByteArray(stream);
        var bytesAsString = Encoding.UTF8.GetString(content);
        return Content(bytesAsString, "image/jpeg").Headers(MimeType);
        }
}

I'm getting NullReferenceException in the ActionResult Download(int) method on content=GetContentToByteArray(stream).
The Stream object is not disposed after reading out some data on the external disk and I'm afraid since the file is still in RAM, the data will be deleted by.Net if Garbage Collector will take the file offline and move it to the Recycle Bin or some such thing.
Does this make more sense and would I run into any problem if I write the result of GetContentToByteArray(stream) directly to disk?

Edit: I'm using ASP.NET MVC 4

A:

Your memory will only be cleaned up by the garbage collector if you did not keep your File stream open, and you don't (even) write anything to the file stream after it is finished.
As long as you keep the FileStream open, you should be safe. When the system is ready to release a file to the recycle bin, it will close the file. The GC won't be called until the end of the request. The GC will call the finalizers and that is all.
