I was looking for the keyword exception to make throw() optional but apparently not.  So then if anyone can think of a way I'd enjoy the challenge.
The problem comes that if you do this, a constructor will be deleted.
template<typename T, typename... Args>
MyClass<T>::MyClass(const MyClass<T, Args...> &) : MyClassBase()
{
    // use the given MyClass class to create an instance of itself here
}

This is the only way I could think of that would solve this problem.  In this case the copy constructor shouldn't try to do anything anyway.

A:

MyClass isn't implicitly copyable for most template types, so it won't work out of the box.
MyClass has a move constructor, so you could make a move constructor, which is essentially a copy constructor. If T doesn't have any non-movable types (i.e. not only static const members, but also member data, or something of that sort), or if you can't have any of your members move, then you're fine. Otherwise, it's a bit messy:
constexpr template <typename T>
MyClass(const MyClass<T> &) : MyClassBase() {}

