Q:

Should I use the `do` statement with callbacks in node.js?

I just discovered that node.js has a nice method to easily create a callback.
Let's assume a function that prints a number a certain number of times:
function printCount(count, number) { 
    for(var i = 0; i < count; ++i) { 
        console.log(number); 
    }
}

printCount(10, "hello");

It is easy to use the node's callback to add a callback to the above function:
var count = 10;
var number = "hello";

printCount(10, function (number2) {
    console.log(number);  // number
    console.log(number2);
});

But, should I create a variable count inside the function and use it and only use the node.js callback function in the last line (second line after the function call)?
var count = 10;

printCount(10, function (number2) {
    console.log(number);  // number
    console.log(number2);
});

Or, should I just use node.js' callback and use the do statement?
var count = 10;

printCount(10, function (number2) {
    do {
        console.log(number);  // number
        console.log(number2);
    } while (--count > 0);
});

Thanks.

A:

When I think of callbacks, I think of three things:
1. Definite
2. Indefinite
3. Definite with a specific context.
1 (definite) vs 3 (definite with context)
When you don't pass in a context, then the callback is an indefinite, so you can assign it a variable and then pass the variable as context.
It's like doing this:
function indefinite(callback) {
  callback(); // call the callback
}

instead of this:
function indefinite(context, callback) {
  callback(); // call the callback in context
}

You can now pass it a value

