@media print {
body {
    color: #000;
}
table,
th,td{
    border: none;
}
}

A:

@media print is broken in IE7, 8, and 8.1.
You will need to do a simple test:
@media print {
body {color:#000; }
table,
th,td{border: none;}
}

If no text is visible, it will work.

Q:

How do I get all the data from an object?

If I make a POST request and the server returns a 500 error, the error would not be returned, just a description of what went wrong.
I want all of the data contained in such an error, in the same way you can do in PHP:
if($mysqli_connect_errno) {
    $response_array["error_message"] = $mysqli_connect_errno;
    echo json_encode($response_array); 
}

How do I do this in python (and maybe all other languages)?

A:

I don't know enough Python, so couldn't answer without some research, but I do know the problem. If you make a HTTP request to a URL like http://example.com/some/where/filename.ext, the HTTP server will return a response code 500 if there is an error in the request. If the server does respond, it is supposed to return the body of the message and all the request headers in the response. Depending on the server implementation, the response may be a chunked message (with a Content-Length header), in which case you should read the bytes from the stream until you get a zero in the byte (chunked messages are terminated with a 0 byte, and so a new chunk will start with 0 bytes). If the server uses chunked encoding, you may be able to work out what the last chunk was and read that byte before you reach the end of the stream, but this is not mandatory, and not in Python either.
You have to read the response stream (or maybe it is the response body stream, I'm not sure) and parse the different headers to work out which format the server used. You may need code like the following to read the response stream and split out different messages:
class ResponseRegex:

