Q:

How to find the number of items of a single array in an unsorted array?

I am very new to programming. If I have an unsorted array and I want to count the maximum number of items I have of a certain property, how may I do this?

A:

The naive solution is to just iterate through the array and count them up. As you go through the array, if you reach the end of the array and there are any instances of the property, increment the resulting variable. You could end with any of the following:

3, as there are 3 items in the array.
4, as there were two pairs of matches.

One better way to do this is to make use of the fact that you know the order of elements in the array. You've also already computed the number of elements in the array, so all you need now is to count the occurrences of that property.
int count = 0;
int max = 0;
for (int i = 0; i < arr.Length; i++) {
  if (arr[i].Property <> null)
    count++;
  if (count > max) {
    max = count;
    // do something with'max'
  }
}

A:

As you were able to identify your elements, you can perform a Set to create an Set and use the count property to determine number of elements:
int numberOfSomething = myCollection.Set<Something>().Count; 

Or if you have elements which have no common properties, you can use the Enumeration Extension method:
int numberOfSomething = myCollection.GetEnumerator().Count();

As you seem to be iterating through your elements, you can simply iterate through them and count them up:
int numberOfSomething = 0;
foreach (Something s in myCollection) {
   if (s.TypeOfSomething!= '') {
      numberOfSomething += 1;
   }
}

If you need to count for a different property, just iterate up again. One reason to take a Set is that by having a known count of items, you can easily keep track that you have something and increment that before you reach the end of the collection.

