Q:

AngularJS - How to detect if a user is online

I want to know if a user is offline or not. 
So I put the following code into '$scope.offline' if the user is offline than the app displays the alert('Offline'). 
That all works fine. But the problem is that I also want to display alerts if the user is using mobile data or wifi for more than X days in a row (so when they are online). What would be the appropriate method to do that?

A:

If you want to display an alert when a user is using mobile data or wifi for more than x days in a row, then you could store X days' duration of time into an ng-repeat with ng-hide. And put a conditional statement inside ng-hide, which will use $rootScope to check the duration against the x days.
<span ui-if='vm.loggedIn && vm.loggedIn.access_token'>
<span ng-if='days == 0;'>Offline</span>
</span>

<span ui-if='vm.hours <= x;'>
<span ng-if='days > 0;'>Wifi, mobile, 3g data etc</span>
</span>

Or you could use $rootScope to create a watcher, which will watch the $window.onunread, $location.url changes and etc.
var app = angular.module('myApp', []);

app.controller('myCtrl', function($rootScope) {
$rootScope.$on('$interval', function() {
  var days = parseInt($rootScope.days, 10);
  $rootScope.days = days;
  if($rootScope.hours >= 12 || $rootScope.hours + $rootScope.minutes >= 72 || $rootScope.hours > 365) {
    $rootScope.$emit('wifi-offline');
  } else {
    $rootScope.$emit('notify-online');
  }

});

})

