Q:

Javascript Function with multiple return values

I have created a little function and I would like to return two strings in different parts.
function myfunt() {
    console.log(1)
    //function code

    console.log(2)
    //another function's code

    return "hello: " + name + ", World!";
}

But when I run it, it gives me only the end result..
(function test() {
    'use strict';
    console.log("inside test");
    // do things
    // do stuff

    myfunt();
})();

myfunt() just displays "hello: x, World!". Not the entire return string

A:

The problem is you are not calling myfunt - you are just invoking it (function test() {...}) - you need to call it.
As mentioned, this is actually not a return statement, but more like a callback - and you need to invoke it from somewhere.
One alternative - if you have the ability to change your myfunt function to accept a callback it would be like
function myfunt() {
   ...
    console.log(name);
    // do things
    // do stuff
   ...
    console.log("hello: " + name + ", World!");
}

And somewhere call that function.
myfunt(function (name) {
    console.log(name);
});

Or, a different approach, call your function from somewhere else after the myfunt is done. (This is basically inline callback)
myfunt();
console.log(myfunt())

